  "output": "## Codebase overview\n\nThis is a pure Python async CLI (job-board scraper + dedup pipeline), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code anywhere in the repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. Here's what I found for the categories that do apply, from `store.py`, `fetchers.py`, `filters.py`, `pipeline.py`, `models.py`.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nThis is the real one. For every job in the batch (which can be thousands — Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Google fetchers each paginate to hundreds+), it runs a separate `SELECT` and a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)   # separate INSERT\n    else:\n        ...                            # separate UPDATE\n```\n\nFor a run pulling ~5k listings across all sources, that's ~10k+ individual SQLite round trips per pipeline run (scheduled every 12h per `notify.py`/README). Fix: batch-fetch existing hashes with one `WHERE key IN (...)`, then use `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # SQLite param limit ~999\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    inserts, updates = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        r = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(r)\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(r)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n            location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range, content_hash,\n            first_seen, last_seen) VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,\n            :location,:department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns O(n) round trips into O(n/900 + 3).\n\n### 2. React re-renders — not applicable\n\nNo `.tsx`/`.jsx`/frontend code exists in this repo. Skipping this category rather than fabricating findings.\n\n### 3. Redundant computations — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex patterns from scratch **for every job**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled per job\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)): # recompiled per job\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls this once per fetched job, so N jobs × M keywords worth of regex compilation happens on every run for the *same* keyword list. Fix — compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (),\n          locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nMinor: `Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66-69`) is a plain `@property` that SHA-256-hashes the same string twice per changed job (once in `Store.diff`'s comparison, again inside `to_row()`). Low cost (short string, small N), not worth restructuring given `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)` (which blocks `functools.cached_property` without adding an explicit slot) — flagging for awareness, not urgent.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunities\n\n- The regex-compilation fix above is the main caching win available.\n- HTTP client reuse is already done well — `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1126-1147`) shares one `httpx.AsyncClient` across all sources via a semaphore, so no fix needed there.\n- No good candidate for response caching across runs — each run's job listings are expected to change, and the dedup already happens at the DB layer.\n\n### 5. Memory leaks\n\nDidn't find any. This is a short-lived CLI process (`agent.py` invoked per scan/run, see README/`modes/pipeline.md`), not a long-running server, so there's no accumulating global state to leak. `Store` is always used via `with Store(...) as store:` (both in `pipeline.py:42` and `agent.py`'s `_store()` callers), so the SQLite connection is closed properly every time. `fetch_all` closes its owned `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` block. No global caches or module-level mutable containers that grow unbounded.\n\n---\n\nWant me to apply the `store.py` batching fix and the `filters.py` regex-hoisting fix? Those are the two changes with real measurable impact; everything else is either N/A or too minor to be worth the churn.\n",
